Kingdom","Dumbarton Castle, Strathclyde, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Dumbarton, Dunbartonshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Polkelly, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mure","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Italian (Sicily): variant of   Morea  .","Scottish: variant of   Muir  .","English: occupational name from Old French <i>muer</i> ‘mewer’, i.e. someone who tended to hawks in the cages in which they were kept while moulting. Compare   Mew  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mura","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Japanese Akio, Hideo, Masao, Nanako, Tsutomu, Yoshi.  French Alphonse, Amie, Henri.","German: altered form of some similar (like-sounding) German or perhaps French surname. It is also common in France (Alsace), where it was first recorded in the form <i>Morrau</i>, later <i>Murra(w)</i>.","Italian (southern Sardinia): topographic name or nickname from Sardinian <i>mura</i> ‘mulberry’ or ‘blackberry’."]},{"name":"Muir","meanings":["Scottish: topographic name for someone who lived on a moor, from Older Scots <i>muir</i> ‘moor’ (an expanse of bare, wild upland country). There has been some confusion with   Mure  ."]},{"name":"Morea","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Saverio, Domenic, Ferdinando, Rocco.  Spanish Manuel, Carlos, Cesar, Elvira, Jesus, Mauricio.","Italian (Apulia): from the personal name <i>Morea</i>, originally a habitational name from Morea, the medieval name of the Greek region of Peloponnese, named as the land of mulberry trees, from <i>mōrea</i> ‘mulberry’.","Spanish and Catalan: habitational name from any of the places called Morea, in Badajoz, Navarre, and Lleida provinces."]}]},{"name":"Gilchrist","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (western) and Irish (Down): from Gaelic <i>Mac Giolla Chríosd</i>, <i>Mac Gille Chríosd</i> ‘son of the servant of Christ’."],"variants":[{"name":"Kilcrease","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Gilchrist  .","History: Robert Kilcrease (<i>c.</i> 1750–1808) came from Scotland(probably Kilmarnock) to Edgefield, SC, <i>c.</i> 1770."]},{"name":"Gilchrest","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Gilchrist  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Gilkerson","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <i>Mac Giolla Chrìosd</i> ‘son of <i>Gille Chrìosd</i>' (see   Gilchrist  )."]},{"name":"Gilkey","meanings":["Irish (northern): possibly a pet form of the Scottishpersonal name   Gilchrist  ."]},{"name":"Gilcrest","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Gilchrist  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Gilcrease","meanings":["Probably an altered form of Scottish   Gilchrist  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gilchrist Mure was born in 1269, in Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, her father, Sir Walter Comyn, was 50 and her mother, Mrs Gilchrist, Earl of Menteith, was 38. She married Sir Hugh de Danzielstoun about 1298, in Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in Dumbarton, Dunbartonshire, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1269–":"1269–Surnud","1269–Female":"1269–Surnud","1266–1317":"1266–1317","1307–1350":"1307–1350","–1355":"–1355","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","1232–Female":"1232–Surnud","Abt 1252":"umbes 1252","1269":"1269","1355":"1355","Abt 1298":"umbes 1298","1266":"1266","1232":"1232","1220":"1220","1350":"1350","1307":"1307","1317":"1317","Dumbarton Castle, Strathclyde, Scotland, ":"Dumbarton, Dunbartonshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Dumbarton Castle, Strathclyde, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Dumbarton, Dunbartonshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Polkelly, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Ayrshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1269–":"1269–Kuollut","1269–Female":"1269–Kuollut","1266–1317":"1266–1317","1307–1350":"1307–1350","–1355":"–1355